🔧 Components Required
🧠 Microcontroller

Arduino Nano (ATmega328P) – Main controller for sensor reading, PID computation, and motor control

👀 Sensors
1️⃣ IR Line Tracking Sensors (3 Units)

TCRT5000-based modules (digital output)

Used for black line detection

Mounted at front underside of chassis

2️⃣ Ultrasonic Sensor – HC-SR04

Used for obstacle detection

Operating voltage: 5V

Measurement range: 2cm – 400cm

⚙️ Motor Driver
L298N Dual H-Bridge Motor Driver Module

Controls direction and speed of 2 DC motors

Supports PWM for speed control

Input voltage: 7V–12V recommended

🚗 Actuators

2 × DC Geared Motors (6V–12V)

1 × Robot Car Chassis (2WD recommended)

2 × Wheels

1 × Castor wheel (for balance)

🔋 Power Supply
Recommended:

7.4V Li-ion Battery Pack (2 × 18650 cells)

Battery holder or BMS module

ON/OFF switch

Not Recommended:

Small rectangular 9V battery ❌

Weak AA cells ❌

💡 Indicators (Optional but Recommended)

3 × LEDs (Green, Yellow, Red)

220Ω resistors (for LEDs)

Active buzzer module (optional)

🔌 Miscellaneous

Breadboard / PCB

Jumper wires (Male-Male, Male-Female)

Screws & spacers

Zip ties (for cable management)

📊 Software Requirements

Arduino IDE

C/C++ (Embedded programming)

PID control algorithm implementation

📦 Optional Upgrade Components (For Future Enhancements)

5-IR Sensor Array (for higher precision PID)

OLED Display (0.96” I2C)

Bluetooth Module (HC-05)

ESP32 (for IoT upgrade)
